Conservation areas are defined in law as 'an area of special architectural or historic interest the character of which it is desirable to preserve and enhance'.
It means if you own or live in a property in a conservation area there will be tighter restrictions making it more likely you will need to apply for planning permission.
You will generally need to apply for planning permission for work including:
  * demolition
  * new development
  * change of use
  * advertisements.

If development proposals involve demolition, as part of your planning application you will need to provide a heritage statement.
This is a statutory requirement and is designed to ensure the application provides a proper assessment of the building/structures significance, its contribution to the conservation area and justify the intended work.
A conservation area also requires notification to be given for works to trees.

  * village design statements
  * flood risk areas
  * our natural and built heritage.

### [ What is neighbourhood planning? ](https://www.easthants.gov.uk/planning-services/planning-policy/neighbourhood-planning/what-neighbourhood-planning)
Successful neighbourhood plans will form part of the development plan used by East Hampshire District Council in determining planning applications.
###

A neighbourhood plan can establish general planning policies for the development and use of land in a neighbourhood, including:
  * where new homes and offices should be built
  * what they should look like
  * what new community facilities are needed and where.

What else can you do?
There are many other ways in which local communities can be involved in planning for the future of their area, for example through the preparation of town and parish plans, or town and village design statements.
The difference between neighbourhood planning and community planning is that neighbourhood planning focuses only on planning issues, whereas documents such as parish plans can cover much wider issues like education and anti-social behaviour.

#  Heritage and trees
East Hampshire is a well wooded district with approximately 17% of its area covered by trees. It is one of the most wooded districts in the country. Trees make a significant contribution to its fine natural qualities and we take our responsibility to protect and enhance these qualities seriously.
